  <validation>
    - Confirm padding oracle by observing different responses
    - Decrypt at least one block of ciphertext
    - Document oracle behavior (error messages, timing, status codes)
    - Forge valid ciphertext for controlled plaintext (if practical)
    - Identify the cryptographic implementation affected
  </validation>

  <false_positives>
    - Error differences due to non-padding issues (network, application logic)
    - Random timing variations below attack threshold
    - Application-level validation before decryption (catches before padding check)
    - Authenticated encryption modes (GCM, CCM) - not vulnerable to padding oracle
  </false_positives>

  <detection_indicators>
    - Many requests with slightly modified encrypted values
    - Sequential byte value testing patterns
    - Unusually high error rates for specific parameters
    - Repeated requests to same endpoint with modified cookies/tokens
  </detection_indicators>

  <pro_tips>
    - CBC mode without authentication is the root cause - recommend GCM/CCM
    - Network jitter can mask timing oracles - use statistical analysis
    - PadBuster is the standard tool for exploitation
    - Some implementations validate MAC before decryption (encrypt-then-MAC) - secure
    - Look for base64 or hex-encoded blobs that are multiples of 8 or 16 bytes
    - ASP.NET ViewState and encrypted cookies are common targets
    - POODLE requires SSL 3.0 downgrade - check TLS version
    - Timing oracles need many samples to reduce noise
  </pro_tips>

  <remember>Padding oracle attacks demonstrate why encrypt-then-MAC or authenticated encryption (AEAD) should always be used. The attack is practical and tools exist to automate exploitation against vulnerable systems.</remember>
</vulnerability_guide>
